offs are made. For some organizations, in particular those organizations that deal with critical
and/or sensitive information, personally identifiable information, or classified information, the
emphasis is often on preventing unauthorized disclosure. In contrast, in those organizations
driven by a combination of organizational culture and the nature of their missions and business
functions, the emphasis is on maintaining the availability of information systems to achieve an
ongoing operational capability. As part of establishing organizational risk tolerance, a risk
assessment identifies the kinds and levels of risk to which organizations may be exposed. This
assessment considers both the likelihood and impact of undesired events (see Chapter Three, the
risk management process).




